00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:22.260
do it either.

00:15:22.260 --> 00:15:25.859
So now you have tools to do this if it works well.

00:15:25.859 --> 00:15:31.219
We also have tools for multi-class models, like three or more classes, and also for regression

00:15:31.219 --> 00:15:32.219
models.

00:15:32.219 --> 00:15:35.619
So if you have a regression model where you plot like the observers as predicted, and

00:15:35.619 --> 00:15:40.099
they sort of like fan off on the end, and you can't find a way to fix that, as sort

00:15:40.099 --> 00:15:45.820
of like, maybe not a last resort, but you could use a similar way to sort of like unbend

00:15:45.820 --> 00:15:49.659
that curve using calibration.

00:15:49.659 --> 00:15:51.580
So now you have this calibration object.

00:15:51.580 --> 00:15:54.619
You have your original model fit.

00:15:54.619 --> 00:15:59.179
The code I showed here is right now how you would apply the calibration.

00:15:59.179 --> 00:16:04.059
That's a little bit more work that we want you to have to do.

00:16:04.059 --> 00:16:09.419
So what we're doing next is we have these objects in tiny models called workflows.

00:16:09.419 --> 00:16:13.299
You can think of them as like scikit-learn pipelines, but Hadley was like, no, don't

00:16:13.299 --> 00:16:15.820
use the word pipeline.

00:16:15.820 --> 00:16:20.659
And so what workflows do is you can bind together a preprocessor, like a recipe, like Emily

00:16:20.659 --> 00:16:22.700
talked about recipes earlier a little bit.

00:16:22.700 --> 00:16:27.619
So you can take a preprocessor object in whatever model you're trying to fit, and you can combine

00:16:27.619 --> 00:16:29.119
them into one object.

00:16:30.059 --> 00:16:34.320
And so next on our list is to add post-processing objects to the workflow.

00:16:34.320 --> 00:16:38.640
So whether it's calibration or optimizing your probability threshold for like a two-class

00:16:38.640 --> 00:16:43.960
system or a variety of things you might do to your data due to your predictions after

00:16:43.960 --> 00:16:48.539
you fit your model, you'll be able to sort of attach like a calibration object.

00:16:48.539 --> 00:16:52.599
So when you use the fit or the predict function at the very end, you don't have to do this

00:16:52.599 --> 00:16:56.400
extra step of holding on to this extra object to then transform your probabilities.

00:16:56.719 --> 00:17:01.520
It'll be built into the workflow, and that'll be a nice little workflow or nice little usability

00:17:01.520 --> 00:17:04.560
feature for people.

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:07.439
We're on a little bit of minutiae here.

00:17:07.439 --> 00:17:10.800
We try to convince everybody to resample everything, right?

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:14.000
That's like our mantra is if you want to get good performance statistics, you have to resample

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:15.800
everything.

00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:20.040
And so when you use a workflow and you resample it, if the workflow does any sort of interesting

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:25.000
estimation parts like feature hashing or some complicated preprocessor, we want to make

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:29.400
sure that gets executed every time freshly with resampling just the same way the model

00:17:29.400 --> 00:17:31.400
does.

00:17:31.400 --> 00:17:35.839
And for the post-processor, that's mostly true, but we're not really exactly sure how

00:17:35.839 --> 00:17:41.339
to make that happen with calibration because if you only have 10% of your data held out

00:17:41.339 --> 00:17:44.400
in that original process, it's weird.

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:49.400
Like when we cross-validated the calibration earlier, we had the 90% of the predictions

00:17:49.479 --> 00:17:55.079
that were held out to do the calibration to then apply to the 10% that are most recently

00:17:55.079 --> 00:17:57.359
held out and compute performance.

00:17:57.359 --> 00:18:00.839
And when we just do normal cross-validation for models and preprocessors, it's a little

00:18:00.839 --> 00:18:02.280
bit the opposite.

00:18:02.280 --> 00:18:06.479
So we're not really sure how we're going to make that work yet, but we will figure it

00:18:06.479 --> 00:18:10.959
out because during regular cross-validation, you only have 10% held out at any time.

00:18:10.959 --> 00:18:14.800
You don't have any of the other data to do the calibration to then measure it.

00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:18.359
So it might take a little bit of work for us to get this going with resampling, but

00:18:18.359 --> 00:18:23.400
I think using calibration in workflow objects should be hopefully before the end of the

00:18:23.400 --> 00:18:24.400
year.

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:25.400
So that's what's on deck.

00:18:25.400 --> 00:18:26.400
Thanks for sticking around.

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:31.959
And just to remind you, Edgar Ruiz did most of the grunt work on this, and so we appreciate

00:18:31.959 --> 00:18:32.959
all the help that he gave.

00:18:32.959 --> 00:18:32.959


